Assembles the two nvim/Plover build artifacts — the Plover dictionary and the LSP snippet table — from a slice of `TypedEntry`, by rendering each through `render_snippet` and routing it based on whether it's terminal.

The core distinction, easy to get wrong when editing: non-terminal entries (type-append intermediates, e.g. partial chords later superseded by a longer stroke) are inserted into `plover_keys` as plain literal text wrapped only in `{^}...{^}` glue — never sentinel-wrapped. Only terminal entries (completed constructs never further extended) get wrapped in `SENTINEL_OPEN`/`SENTINEL_CLOSE` and registered in `snippets` keyed by `key_id`. This matters because the nvim plugin rewrites sentinel tokens into full snippet bodies; if a non-terminal partial were sentinel-wrapped and expanded before Plover's later backspace-correction fires, Plover's backspace count would no longer match the buffer contents and it would eat surrounding text. Getting terminal/non-terminal classification wrong silently corrupts editor output, not a crash.

Both non-terminal and terminal Plover values are prefixed/suffixed with `{^}` glue — required because Plover otherwise inserts a leading space before glueless translations, which would throw off token alignment relative to surrounding code.

`build_snippets(entries: &[TypedEntry]) -> Result<SnippetBuild, SnippetError>` is the sole entry point, returning a `SnippetBuild { plover_keys, snippets, collisions }`. `SnippetBuild.collisions` accumulates `key_id`s where two entries mapped the same stroke to different values (non-terminal: different literal bodies; terminal: different snippet bodies) — collisions are recorded but not fatal; the last-inserted value wins in both maps since `insert_non_terminal`/`insert_terminal` always overwrite. Depends on `render_snippet` and `SnippetEntry` (sibling module) for per-entry rendering, and `OrderedMap` from `json_out` to preserve deterministic key ordering in the emitted JSON artifacts.